  "result": "I'll create this reference doc. Let me build it directly as my output.\n\n# 🧠 The Algorithms Mastery Bootcamp — Project Bank\n\n> **How to use this:** Pick a concept. Do *several* projects per concept — warmup first to wake the muscle, then climb toward research-grade. You never re-read theory; you *re-derive* it by building. Each project drills one specific sub-skill. **`[SIM]`** = a simulation/benchmark/visualization (you'll generate plots and *watch* the asymptotics, not just believe them). The **bold flagship** in each concept is the one to brag about.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Sorting & Divide-and-Conquer\n*The merge step is a Swiss Army knife. Sorting isn't a chore — it's how you expose hidden structure.*\n\n- [ ] **Inversion Counter** `warmup` — mergesort that returns the sorted array *and* the exact inversion count in one O(n log n) pass, wired into a real \"taste twin\" movie recommender. *Drills: carrying an accumulator through the merge without breaking the recurrence.* · [CS170 notes](https://theory.stanford.edu/~trevisan/cs170/notes/book.pdf)\n- [ ] **Pattern Recognition (Collinear Points)** `core` — render every maximal 4+-point line in a star field by sorting points by slope. *Drills: stable vs unstable sort, custom comparators, \"sort to expose structure.\"* · [Princeton COS226](https://www.cs.princeton.edu/courses/archive/fall11/cos226/checklist/collinear.html)\n- [ ] **Closest Pair on a Continent** `core` `[SIM]` — D&C nearest-two-points among millions; benchmark harness plots measured comparison counts hugging the n log n fit. *Drills: the strip argument, constant-7 packing bound, why COMBINE cost picks your Master Theorem case.* · [walkthrough](https://medium.com/@shihyu-wu/algorithms-studynote-4-divide-and-conquer-closest-pair-49ba679ce3c7)\n- [ ] **AntiQuicksort: Build the Adversary** `stretch` `[SIM]` — an adversary comparator that decides element values *as your quicksort probes them*, forcing O(n²) on any deterministic pivot; then introsort refuses to die. *Drills: Lomuto vs Hoare, recursion-depth blowup, why production sorts are hybrids.* · [McIlroy's killer adversary / Introsort](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Introsort)\n- [ ] **Worst-Case Selection (Median of Medians)** `research-grade` `[SIM]` — guaranteed-linear k-th smallest, powering a p99-latency Top-K service; plot comps/n flatlining to a constant. *Drills: the T(n) ≤ T(n/5)+T(7n/10)+O(n) geometric-sum recurrence where the Master Theorem doesn't apply, and why the magic number is five.* · [BFPRT / Median of medians](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median_of_medians)\n\n---\n\n## 2. Hashing & Hash Tables\n*Load factor is the one knob. Randomize the hash and the adversary loses.*\n\n- [ ] **MyHashMap + Probe-Count Microscope** `warmup` `[SIM]` — chaining and open-addressing in one codebase; plot average probe count vs load factor α, watch linear probing fall off the cliff at exactly the α theory predicts. *Drills: collision resolution, amortized O(1) via doubling.* · [CS61B Lab09](https://fa23.datastructur.es/materials/lab/lab09/)\n- [ ] **The Adversary: hashDoS, then Universal Hashing** `core` `[SIM]` — build a working complexity-attack that turns a hash table into a tarpit, then neutralize it with `((a·x+b) mod p) mod m` and a coin flip. *Drills: why fixed hashes have no worst-case guarantee, Pr[h(x)=h(y)] ≤ 1/m.*\n- [ ] **FKS + Cuckoo: zero-collision guarantees** `stretch` `[SIM]` — two routes to worst-case O(1) lookup; sweep α to discover the ~0.5 cuckoo phase-transition cliff *before anyone tells you the number*. *Drills: FKS quadratic-inner/linear-total space, cuckoo eviction.* · [CS166](https://www.keithschwarz.com/cs166/)\n- [ ] **Membership-Filter Shootout** `stretch` `[SIM]` — Bloom vs Counting-Bloom vs Cuckoo filter on a real URL blocklist; reproduce the published crossover where Cuckoo beats Bloom *and* supports deletes. *Drills: optimal k = (m/n)ln2, space/FPR/feature tradeoffs.* · [Cuckoo filter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cuckoo_filter)\n- [ ] **MPHF at Scale: ~2 bits/key on 10M keys** `research-grade` `[SIM]` — bijective minimal perfect hash over 10M URLs/words near the 1.44-bits/key information floor; chart your numbers against RecSplit/PTHash. *Drills: hypergraph peeling / recursive splitting, the bits-per-key frontier.* · [RecSplit](https://arxiv.org/pdf/1910.06416) · [PTHash](https://jermp.github.io/assets/pdf/papers/SIGIR2021.pdf)\n\n---\n\n## 3. Binary Search Trees & Balanced Trees\n*Height — not node count — is the whole game.*\n\n- [ ] **Height Race Simulator (BST vs AVL vs RB vs Treap vs Splay)** `warmup` `[SIM]` — feed five trees the SAME adversarial streams; watch naive-BST height go vertical on sorted input while balanced trees stay flat, and the splay tree's cost curve *bend downward* as it learns a Zipf workload. *Drills: worst-case vs expected vs amortized, the real height constants.* · [COS226 lecture](https://www.cs.princeton.edu/courses/archive/fall12/cos226/lectures/33BalancedSearchTrees.pdf)\n- [ ] **Kd-Tree Spatial Index + Boids Flocking** `core` `[SIM]` — a 2d-tree powering a live murmuration of hundreds of boids via k-NN queries; op-counter shows pruning crushing brute force. *Drills: BST generalized to multidim keys, the rectangle-distance pruning bound.* · [COS226 Kd-Trees](https://www.cs.princeton.edu/courses/archive/fall19/cos226/assignments/kdtree/specification.php)\n- [ ] **🚩 Disk-Backed B+Tree Storage Engine** `stretch` — a real on-disk paged B+Tree with a buffer pool, splits/merges, and a crash/reopen test: **the indexing core of SQLite/Postgres/MySQL, built by you.** *Drills: high fan-out to minimize I/O, routing-vs-data node separation.* · [CMU 15-445 Project 2](https://15445.courses.cs.cmu.edu/fall2024/project2/)\n- [ ] **Cache-Oblivious vEB-Layout Search Tree** `stretch` `[SIM]` — three trees, identical Big-O, but the vEB layout is several× faster on large n; cache-miss plot shows exactly why, with the crossover landing where data outgrows cache. *Drills: the O(log_B n) I/O bound with no knowledge of B.* · [MIT 6.851](https://courses.csail.mit.edu/6.851/)\n- [ ] **Tango Trees + Interleave Lower-Bound Verifier** `research-grade` `[SIM]` — implement a 2004 result and watch your tree stay within a log-log factor of an optimum it can't see; then poke at the still-open dynamic-optimality conjecture. *Drills: preferred-path decomposition, cut/merge, Wilber-style lower bounds.* · [Tango tree](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tango_tree)\n\n---\n\n## 4. Heaps & Priority Queues\n*A local invariant restored by O(log n) swaps — and the heartbeat of every best-first search.*\n\n- [ ] **ArrayHeap + Invariant Fuzzer** `warmup` — index-arithmetic binary heap, then a differential fuzzer that mirrors every op against a reference and auto-shrinks any failure to a minimal counterexample. *Drills: sink/swim, the heap property as a local invariant, O(n) bottom-up heapify.* · [CS61B ArrayHeap](https://inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~cs61b/sp20/materials/lab/lab9/index.html)\n- [ ] **A*/Dijkstra Slider-Puzzle & Road Router** `core` — your indexed heap drives an 8/15-puzzle solver (Manhattan vs Hamming node counts) and Dijkstra over a real OSM road network, using real decrease-key. *Drills: priority = cost+heuristic, stable handles for decrease-key, admissibility.* · [COS226 8-Puzzle](https://coursera.cs.princeton.edu/algs4/assignments/8puzzle.html)\n- [ ] **Seam Carving as Heap-Backed Shortest Path** `stretch` — content-aware image resize + object removal via min-energy seams; the same Photoshop \"Content-Aware Scale,\" falling out of the relaxation machinery. *Drills: modeling 2-D problems as shortest paths, distTo/edgeTo relaxation.* · [COS226 Seam](https://www.cs.princeton.edu/courses/archive/spr18/cos226/assignments/seam/checklist.html)\n- [ ] **🚩 The Great Heap Race** `research-grade` `[SIM]` — binary vs d-ary vs binomial vs Fibonacci vs pairing behind one interface, instrumented with cache misses: **produce the plot every textbook describes but never shows — the Fibonacci heap getting smoked by a humble 4-ary heap because of cache lines**, and derive the optimal d yourself. *Drills: the full taxonomy + amortized bounds, and constants/cache beating asymptotics.* · [d-ary heap](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D-ary_heap)\n- [ ] **Streaming Top-K & Online Median** `stretch` `[SIM]` — bounded-memory analytics over a billion-event stream using only heaps (size-K top-K, two-heaps median, sliding-window max, k-way external merge); dashboard proves memory stays flat. *Drills: heaps as online tools, the |low|−|high|∈{0,1} median invariant.* · [algs4 PQ](https://algs4.cs.princeton.edu/24pq/)\n\n---\n\n## 5. Graphs I — Traversal & Shortest Paths\n*BFS floods, Dijkstra weights, A\\* aims. h=0 *is* Dijkstra.*\n\n- [ ] **Word Ladder & Six-Degrees Oracle** `warmup` — multi-source BFS over a real friendship graph; rediscover the small-world phenomenon (everyone within ~4–5 hops) and watch \"no ladder exists\" fall out of disconnected components. *Drills: BFS as unweighted SSSP, parent-pointer reconstruction, implicit vs explicit graphs.* · [COS226 WordNet/SAP](https://coursera.cs.princeton.edu/algs4/assignments/wordnet/specification.php)\n- [ ] **Trailblazer: BFS vs Dijkstra vs A\\* on a Live Grid** `core` `[SIM]` — animated terrain pathfinder; *see* Dijkstra flood in a circle while A\\* drives a narrow beam at the goal, then sabotage A\\* with an inadmissible heuristic and watch the path go suboptimal. *Drills: the exact g(n) vs g(n)+h(n) distinction, the settled-set invariant.* · [Stanford CS106B](https://web.stanford.edu/class/archive/cs/cs106b/cs106b.1182/assn/Trailblazer.html)\n- [ ] **🚩 Bear Maps: A\\* over Real OpenStreetMap** `stretch` — parse a city's `.osm`, route door-to-door with a haversine heuristic, generate turn-by-turn directions and Trie autocomplete: **a genuine, demoable mini-Google-Maps you built from an XML file and a priority queue.** *Drills: admissible/consistent geometric heuristics, cleaning real data, decrease-key at scale.* · [CS61B Bear Maps](https://sp18.datastructur.es/materials/proj/proj3/proj3)\n- [ ] **Arbitrage Hunter (Bellman-Ford negative cycles)** `stretch` — model FX rates as −log(r) edges; a profitable loop becomes a negative cycle, and your program prints the actual trades that turn $1 into $1.007 for free. *Drills: why Dijkstra fails on negative edges, the V−1 rounds + one extra certifying round, the −log transform.* · [CS170 FX arbitrage](https://people.eecs.berkeley.edu/~daw/teaching/cs170-s03/Notes/lecture7.pdf)\n- [ ] **Shortest-Path Asymptotics Shootout** `research-grade` `[SIM]` — race BFS/Dijkstra(heap vs array)/Bellman-Ford/A\\* across graph families; find the density crossover where the array PQ *wins*, and watch h=0 reproduce Dijkstra cell-for-cell. *Drills: Big-O → measured curves, A\\* expansions vs heuristic quality, benchmarking hygiene.*\n\n---\n\n## 6. Graphs II — MST, Network Flow & Matching\n*The max-flow / min-cut / matching trinity is one idea wearing three costumes.*\n\n- [ ] **MST Algorithm Race (Kruskal vs Prim vs Borůvka)** `warmup` `[SIM]` — density sweeps where you watch the Kruskal and Prim curves physically cross, and point at the near-flat union-find slope and say \"that's inverse Ackermann.\" *Drills: cut/cycle property, α(n) amortized analysis, removing path compression to see a curve bend up.*\n- [ ] **Baseball Elimination + Min-Cut Certificates** `core` — max-flow feasibility decides who's mathematically eliminated, and prints the actual subset of teams (the min-cut) that proves it; reproduce the 1996 Tigers. *Drills: modeling constraints as flow, max-flow/min-cut duality as an explanation, integrality.* · [COS226 Baseball](https://coursera.cs.princeton.edu/algs4/assignments/baseball.html)\n- [ ] **🚩 Graph-Cut Image Segmentation** `stretch` `[SIM]` — scribble foreground/background seeds; max-flow's min-cut *literally cuts a person out of a photo*. Edmonds-Karp for correctness, then Dinic's for megapixels, with augmenting-path counts proving the speedup as a stopwatch number. *Drills: min-cut as global energy minimizer, blocking flows / level graphs, t-link/n-link construction.* · [seg writeup](https://julie-jiang.github.io/image-segmentation/)\n- [ ] **Min-Cost Max-Flow Job Scheduler + Hungarian Oracle** `stretch` — min-cost perfect matching via successive shortest augmenting paths, cross-validated against Hungarian on thousands of instances (a proof-by-cross-check of LP duality), plus König's min vertex cover from the residual graph. *Drills: matching as unit-capacity flow, Johnson potentials, König's theorem as executable invariant.*\n- [ ] **Augmenting-Path Pathology Lab** `research-grade` `[SIM]` — manufacture the worst-case network and watch naive Ford-Fulkerson grind 2000 augmentations while Edmonds-Karp finishes in 2; sweep capacity to render strongly- vs pseudo-polynomial as two lines on one chart. *Drills: EK's O(VE²), Dinic's O(V²E), capacity-scaling.*\n\n---\n\n## 7. Dynamic Programming\n*Recover the *path*, not just the cost. Then do it in linear space.*\n\n- [ ] **Diff & Autocorrect Engine** `warmup` — the literal core of `git diff` plus weighted-edit-distance autocorrect; implement the O(mn) backtrace, then re-derive byte-identical alignments in Hirschberg's O(min(m,n)) space. *Drills: the edit-distance recurrence, path recovery via parent pointers, the linear-space D&C trick that makes genome alignment feasible.* · [MIT 6.046 DP set](https://people.csail.mit.edu/bdean/6.046/dp/)\n- [ ] **Seam Carver (Content-Aware Resize)** `core` `[SIM]` — recognize a pixel grid as an implicit DAG; animate the min-energy seam wriggling around a face and getting plucked, plus mask-based object removal. *Drills: topological-order DP relaxation from 3 predecessors, local-recompute-only energy.* · [COS226 Seam](https://www.cs.princeton.edu/courses/archive/spring21/cos226/assignments/seam/specification.php)\n- [ ] **0/1 Knapsack Solver Arena** `stretch` `[SIM]` — exact DP vs branch-and-bound vs greedy vs an ε-FPTAS; hold n fixed, slide W up, and *watch weak NP-hardness happen* as the \"efficient\" DP curve bends while B&B implodes on correlated instances. *Drills: pseudo-polynomiality, weight- vs value-indexed DP, the FPTAS accuracy/runtime curve.* · [MIT 6.006 knapsack](https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/6-006-introduction-to-algorithms-fall-2011/resources/recitation-21-dynamic-programming-knapsack-problem/)\n- [ ] **RNA Folder (Nussinov + Zuker)** `stretch` — interval DP that folds a 1-D string of letters into a hairpin you can draw; the bifurcation case `dp[i][j]=max_k dp[i][k]+dp[k+1][j]` shared with matrix-chain and optimal BST. *Drills: interval DP in increasing-length order, backtracing a 2-D table into a nested structure.* · [Nussinov](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nussinov_algorithm)\n- [ ] **🚩 Treewidth Engine: DP That Beats NP-Hardness** `research-grade` `[SIM]` — tree-decompose any graph and run Leaf/Introduce/Forget/Join DP to *exactly* solve Max-Weight Independent Set / Vertex Cover / Dominating Set; plot runtime exploding as treewidth climbs while staying linear in n. **NP-hardness isn't about the problem — it's about the graph's shape.** *Drills: DP-on-trees with exponential bag-tables, the 2^k·n bound, Courcelle's theorem in practice.* · [Tree decomposition](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_decomposition)\n\n---\n\n## 8. Greedy Algorithms & Amortized Analysis\n*Greedy stays ahead — and the potential function is a live gauge you can watch.*\n\n- [ ] **Percolation Threshold Estimator** `warmup` `[SIM]` — Monte Carlo + weighted quick-union discovers the ~0.593 phase transition of a 2-D lattice; feel WQU vs quick-find as the gap between \"instant\" and \"hangs.\" *Drills: union-find for incremental connectivity, the virtual-node trick.* · [COS226 Percolation](https://coursera.cs.princeton.edu/algs4/assignments/percolation.html)\n- [ ] **Huffman Codec + Exchange-Argument Visualizer** `core` `[SIM]` — a working compressor *and* a watchable proof: animate the swap that proves the two rarest symbols can be deepest siblings, and plot compressed size hugging Shannon entropy. *Drills: the greedy-stays-ahead exchange argument as a cut-and-paste swap.* · [CS170](https://people.eecs.berkeley.edu/~jrs/170/)\n- [ ] **Kruskal Maze Forge** `stretch` `[SIM]` — MST-driven maze generation where colored disjoint-set islands fuse live into one perfect maze, with a path-compression-vs-not overlay against the α(n) bound. *Drills: union-find as Kruskal's cycle oracle, watching path compression flatten the forest.*\n- [ ] **Potential-Method Lab** `stretch` `[SIM]` — aggregate vs accounting vs potential on a dynamic array, binary counter, and multipop stack; watch all three agree on the same trace, then sabotage the growth factor (+1 not ×2) and watch elegant O(1) shatter into O(n). *Drills: choosing a valid Φ, amortized = real + ΔΦ, why geometric resizing is load-bearing.*\n- [ ] **🚩 Dynamic-Optimality Arena (Splay vs the World)** `research-grade` `[SIM]` — verify the splay access lemma's potential inequality on *every single op*, then race splay trees against the Wilber interleave lower bound on adversarial sequences — **the same experiments researchers run attacking a 40-year-old open problem.** *Drills: the sum-of-log-ranks potential, working-set/static-finger theorems, competitive ratios.* · [MIT 6.851](https://courses.csail.mit.edu/6.851/)\n\n---\n\n## 9. Randomized & Streaming Algorithms\n*A random number per node buys adversary-proof balance for free; a kilobyte counts a billion.*\n\n- [ ] **Streaming Sampler (Reservoir + Permutation)** `warmup` — one-pass uniform sampling from an unknown-length firehose (Algorithm R, then L's geometric jumps); chi-square test passes while memory stays flat at O(k). *Drills: P(survive)=k/n by induction, amortized O(1) randomized queue.* · [COS226 Queues](https://coursera.cs.princeton.edu/algs4/assignments/queues/specification.php)\n- [ ] **Treap vs BST Height Race** `core` `[SIM]` — identical sorted input, identical interface; one structure crawls at O(n), the other hugs ~2 ln n — *the only difference is a random priority per node.* *Drills: decoupling performance from input order, the Cartesian-tree invariant, w.h.p. depth.* · [Treap](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treap)\n- [ ] **Skip List as Indexed Ordered Map** `core` `[SIM]` — the structure behind LevelDB/RocksDB memtables and Java's lock-free sorted map, upgraded with span-based rank/select; dial p and watch measured comparisons slide along the theoretical tradeoff curve. *Drills: coin-flip promotion, geometric heights, the p space/time knob.* · [Skip list](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skip_list)\n- [ ] **Count-Min Sketch Heavy Hitters** `stretch` `[SIM]` — top-K over a real high-cardinality stream; widen the sketch and watch measured error tuck under the ε·N envelope while the exact hash-map OOMs. *Drills: MIN over d rows for one-sided error, (ε,δ)→(w,d) sizing.* · [CS168](https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs168/l/l2.pdf)\n- [ ] **🚩 Build Redis's HyperLogLog** `research-grade` `[SIM]` — count distinct items over the whole internet in a fixed 12 KB; implement dense+sparse registers and the merge op, then plot relative error flattening to a 0.81% band against the 1.04/√m law **while a HashSet of the same data eats gigabytes.** *Drills: leading-zero-run cardinality estimation, harmonic-mean stochastic averaging, mergeability.* · [HyperLogLog](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HyperLogLog) · [antirez](https://antirez.com/news/75)\n\n---\n\n## 10. Advanced Data Structures\n*The RAM model is a lie — and persistence is the magic behind Git.*\n\n- [ ] **The Predecessor Arena (vEB / x-fast / y-fast)** `core` `[SIM]` — four structures, log-log query curves, *and* a cache-miss plot showing vEB's theoretical win evaporate on real hardware because pointer-chasing blows L1/L2. *Drills: the O(log log M) bound, the vEB→x-fast→y-fast space/time ladder.* · [MIT 6.851](https://courses.csail.mit.edu/6.851/)\n- [ ] **Git-in-a-Box: Fully Persistent Edit History** `core` — fat-node + node-copying persistent BST powering a tiny VCS with branch/checkout/diff/merge from *any* past version, with O(total edits) storage. *Drills: partial vs full vs confluent persistence, why bounded in-degree gives O(1) node-copying.*\n- [ ] **Retroactive Priority Queue** `stretch` — Insert/Delete-min *into the past*, then watch a live Dijkstra shortest-path tree self-heal after an edge weight is corrected — in log time, not a recompute. *Drills: retroactivity ≠ persistence, the Delete-min cascade, bracket-matching for O(log m).*\n- [ ] **Cache-Oblivious Showdown** `stretch` `[SIM]` — a vEB-laid-out search tree + cache-oblivious matrix multiply that ties or beats a hand-tuned B-tree across *every* cache level without ever reading B. *Drills: the ideal-cache I/O model, Θ(n³/(B√M)) multiply, \"oblivious beats aware.\"*\n- [ ] **🚩 FM-Index: Search a Genome Below Its Own Size** `research-grade` — O(1)-rank bitvector + wavelet tree + BWT backward search; load a real chromosome, index it *below the nH₀ entropy bound*, and locate any pattern in O(|P|). **The structure inside Bowtie/BWA that made the $200 genome possible** — reported at, say, 2.1 bits/base. *Drills: succinct vs compressed, superblock/block rank, BWT+rank composing into self-indexing.* · [Succinct](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Succinct_data_structure)\n\n---\n\n## 11. String Algorithms\n*A trie answers \"could this be a prefix?\" — the query that kills exponential blowup.*\n\n- [ ] **Boggle Solver (Trie-Pruned DFS)** `warmup` — walk a trie in lockstep with grid DFS; prune the instant the prefix dies, turning exponential search near-linear (3–4 orders of magnitude fewer nodes). *Drills: the trie as a pruning oracle, why a hash set can't do this.* · [COS226 Boggle](https://coursera.cs.princeton.edu/algs4/assignments/boggle/specification.php)\n- [ ] **KMP vs Brute vs Rabin-Karp Race Track** `core` `[SIM]` — build the `aaaa…ab` worst case to make brute force visibly explode while KMP stays a straight line, then weaponize a hash collision to humiliate Rabin-Karp. *Drills: the failure/border function, monotone text pointer, rolling-hash recurrence.* · [algs4 substring](https://algs4.cs.princeton.edu/53substring/)\n- [ ] **Aho-Corasick Intrusion/Motif Scanner** `stretch` — match thousands of patterns in *one* pass (the engine inside `fgrep` and Snort); benchmark shows per-pattern-KMP blowing past it linearly. *Drills: generalizing KMP's failure fn to a trie, BFS-order goto/fail/output construction.* · [Aho-Corasick](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aho%E2%80%93Corasick_algorithm)\n- [ ] **Suffix Array + LCP Toolkit** `stretch` — prefix-doubling SA + Kasai's amortized-linear LCP; find \"the longest passage that repeats in *War and Peace*\" or the longest exact repeat in a chromosome, array-only. *Drills: rank-pair doubling, Kasai's drop-by-at-most-1 trick, queries by reduction to SA+LCP.* · [CS166](https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs166/)\n- [ ] **🚩 Burrows-Wheeler + FM-Index** `research-grade` — build *both* a lossless compressor rivaling bzip2's core AND, from the same transform, a backward-search read aligner that locates a pattern in a billion-base genome in near-compressed space. **The compression artifact doubles as a full-text search index** — one of the genuinely jaw-dropping results in CS. *Drills: BWT from the suffix array, LF-mapping, C[]+rank backward search.* · [COS226 Burrows](https://coursera.cs.princeton.edu/algs4/assignments/burrows/specification.php)\n\n---\n\n## 12. Computational Geometry & Spatial Structures\n*One primitive — the cross-product orientation test — unlocks half the field.*\n\n- [ ] **Collinear Points + Convex-Hull Onion Peeling** `warmup` — sort-by-slope line detection, Graham scan, then peel hull after hull into convex layers (a real robust-statistics object). *Drills: ccw as the single primitive, the Graham-scan stack invariant, degeneracy without floating-point comparisons.* · [COS226 Collinear](https://coursera.cs.princeton.edu/algs4/assignments/collinear/specification.php)\n- [ ] **2d-Tree Range Search + Nearest Neighbor** `core` — drag the mouse and watch the tree light up only the handful of cells it probes against a brute-force baseline highlighting every point. *Drills: split-axis alternation, per-node bounding boxes, near-subtree-first to enable far-subtree pruning.* · [COS226 Kd-Trees](https://coursera.cs.princeton.edu/algs4/assignments/kdtree/specification.php)\n- [ ] **k-d Tree vs Linear Scan: Curse-of-Dimensionality** `stretch` `[SIM]` — sweep d=2…30 and produce the single plot that explains why FAISS/Annoy/HNSW exist: the crossover where your beautiful log tree becomes slower than a dumb for-loop. *Drills: why pruning stops firing as a hypersphere fills a vanishing fraction of its box; exact vs (1+ε)-approx.*\n- [ ] **🚩 Bentley-Ottmann Sweep Line** `stretch` `[SIM]` — report all K segment intersections in O((N+K) log N) with an animated sweep where the status BST reorders *exactly* at each crossing; **the cleanest output-sensitive-complexity demo in all of algorithms**, confirmed against the quadratic baseline. *Drills: event-queue + ordered-status pattern, the adjacency invariant, disciplined degeneracy handling.* · [Bentley-Ottmann](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bentley%E2%80%93Ottmann_algorithm)\n- [ ] **Persistent Segment/Range Tree for Point Location** `research-grade` `[SIM]` — path-copy a segment tree into N snapshots for O(log N) planar point location in O(N) space, plus a 2-D range tree where fractional cascading visibly erases a log factor from the query curve. *Drills: segment/range-tree augmentation, persistence by path-copying, fractional cascading.* · [MIT 6.851](https://courses.csail.mit.edu/6.851/)\n\n---\n\n## 13. Complexity, NP-Completeness & Lower Bounds\n*A reduction isn't abstract — it's a compiler. Hardness is a phase transition you can plot.*\n\n- [ ] **The Reduction Compiler (Puzzle → SAT → Puzzle)** `warmup` — compile Sudoku to CNF gadgets, solve with MiniSat, decode back; a generic Boolean engine that knows nothing about Sudoku solves your newspaper puzzle. *Drills: poly-time many-one reductions, solution-preservation both directions, \"in NP = poly-checkable certificate.\"* · [Gadgets](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gadget_(computer_science))\n- [ ] **Karp's Web: An Executable Reduction Graph** `core` — implement each edge of the 3SAT→CLIQUE→VC→HAM→TSP DAG; transport one instance along any path and watch a TSP tour pop out that secretly solves your Sudoku, property-tested at every hop. *Drills: transitivity/composability of reductions, the canonical gadget catalogue.* · [Karp's 21](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karp%27s_21_NP-complete_problems)\n- [ ] **Phase-Transition Lab** `core` `[SIM]` — sweep random-3SAT clause ratio α; watch satisfiability crash from ~1 to ~0 right as solver cost peaks near α_c ≈ 4.27, and watch the transition sharpen toward a step function as n grows. *Drills: worst-case ≠ typical-case hardness, finite-size scaling, the computational phase transition.* · [SATLIB](https://www.cs.ubc.ca/~hoos/SATLIB/Benchmarks/SAT/RND3SAT/descr.html)\n- [ ] **The Approximation Arena** `stretch` `[SIM]` — CS170-tournament-style leaderboard for Metric-TSP & Vertex Cover: Christofides (1.5×) and maximal-matching (2×) vs simulated annealing / 2-opt, with live empirical ratios — *and the wall where VC refuses to drop below ~2 no matter how clever you get.* *Drills: provable ratios, empirical-vs-worst-case gap, the inapproximability barrier made tangible.* · [Hardness of approx](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hardness_of_approximation)\n- [ ] **🚩 Prove-It-Hard: An Original Hardness Proof + Verifier** `research-grade` — pick a puzzle/game, reduce 3SAT (or NCL) into *playable levels* whose only winning strategy encodes a satisfying assignment, with a verifier checking the iff against brute force; write it up Demaine-style. **The actual content of an MIT grad course, turned into a buildable artifact.** *Drills: choosing the right hard source, variable/clause/crossover gadgets, planarity, NP-hard vs PSPACE-hard.* · [MIT 6.890](https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/6-890-algorithmic-lower-bounds-fun-with-hardness-proofs-fall-2014/)\n\n---\n\n## 🏆 Hall of Fame — The Portfolio Centerpieces\n\nThe ~12 flagships that make people lean in. If you build nothing else, build these — each is a demoable, \"wait, *you* built that?\" artifact.\n\n1. **Disk-Backed B+Tree Storage Engine** *(BSTs)* — the indexing core of SQLite/Postgres, on real pages, surviving crashes. · [15-445](https://15445.courses.cs.cmu.edu/fall2024/project2/)\n2. **FM-Index: Search a Genome Below Its Own Size** *(Advanced DS / Strings)* — the structure inside Bowtie/BWA; you beat the information-theoretic floor.\n3. **Burrows-Wheeler + FM-Index Compressor & Aligner** *(Strings)* — one transform that compresses *and* self-indexes a billion-base genome. · [Burrows](https://coursera.cs.princeton.edu/algs4/assignments/burrows/specification.php)\n4. **Build Redis's HyperLogLog** *(Randomized)* — a billion distinct items in 12 KB, error pinned to 0.81%. · [antirez](https://antirez.com/news/75)\n5. **Bear Maps: A\\* over OpenStreetMap** *(Graphs I)* — a mini-Google-Maps with turn-by-turn directions from an XML file. · [Bear Maps](https://sp18.datastructur.es/materials/proj/proj3/proj3)\n6. **Graph-Cut Image Segmentation** *(Graphs II)* — max-flow's min-cut literally cuts a person out of a photo.\n7. **Treewidth Engine: DP That Beats NP-Hardness** *(DP)* — exactly solve NP-hard problems by paying 2^treewidth; the engine behind Courcelle's theorem.\n8. **The Great Heap Race** *(Heaps)* — the plot textbooks describe but never show: a 4-ary heap smoking the Fibonacci heap on cache. · [d-ary](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D-ary_heap)\n9. **Dynamic-Optimality Arena (Splay vs Wilber)** *(Greedy/Amortized)* — run the same experiments researchers use to attack a 40-year-old open problem. · [6.851](https://courses.csail.mit.edu/6.851/)\n10. **Bentley-Ottmann Sweep Line** *(Geometry)* — the cleanest output-sensitive-complexity animation in all of algorithms. · [B-O](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bentley%E2%80%93Ottmann_algorithm)\n11. **Prove-It-Hard: Original Hardness Proof + Verifier** *(Complexity)* — playable levels whose only win encodes a SAT assignment; MIT 6.890, shipped. · [6.890](https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/6-890-algorithmic-lower-bounds-fun-with-hardness-proofs-fall-2014/)\n12. **Git-in-a-Box: Fully Persistent Edit History** *(Advanced DS)* — Git's structural-sharing magic, rebuilt from a persistence transform on a search tree.\n\n*Pick one tonight. The plot you generate will teach you more than any chapter you'd re-read.*"
}